item.title: Deathbringer
item.dc:creator: @the_wanderer The Wanderer
item.description:
@the_wanderer wrote:

[quote=“SilentCJ, post:43, topic:343959”][quote author=the wanderer link=topic=440341.msg3444019#msg3444019 date=1293277339]
What I mean is drawing lines and playing connect the dots. Sorry for the misunderstanding.
[/quote]
But you can do that aswell… I know you can in Maya, 3ds Max, and Cinema 4D, so :P.[/quote]
I guess you can. I never figured out how because I never needed to haha.

[quote=“Timberpig., post:44, topic:343959”]yeah i dont really understand why all of you freak out about tracing, well i mean like nice tracing because less experienced modellers trace and make horrid wire frames…
but if i trace and make a neat wireframe, it shouldnt matter, right?[/quote]
Yes, but your wireframe will be neat because you know how a create a good polygonal flow from the usage of primitives. So all in all, primitives will let you progress faster. It will take you longer to learn how to create a good polygonal flow tracing that using primitives. I posted a topic one time on how to create a nice flow using tracing, but everyone that traces couldn’t follow it and all of the people that could follow it used primitives. So it defeated the purpose.

Read full topic

item.title: Deathbringer
item.dc:creator: @SilentCJ SilentCJ
item.description:
@SilentCJ wrote:

[quote=“the wanderer, post:40, topic:343959”][quote author=dylan_0789 link=topic=440341.msg3443937#msg3443937 date=1293264197]

What’s wrong with you people?! Why the hell would you say it looks traced if it’s a flippin’ amazing model? Who cares if it’s traced? Does it look amazing? Yes. It would hardly be different if it wasn’t traced…

This model looks fantastic, in my opinion. Great job. Don’t let people bring you down because “0mg itz traiced!”. Those people don’t what they are talking about.

Wait WTF? Massive grave-dig?

Because tracing is an sign of inexperienced modeling skills in which the modeler is unable to see how the use of primitive manipulation is of more use than the simple plot-point trace method.
[/quote]
And because you can’t even trace in more advanced modelling programs haha.[/quote]
Yes you can…

Most of the professionals will either do what you call tracing, or have an image of the object they are modelling right next to them. You can still trace using primitives, all it does is help get the proportionality correct.

Read full topic
